ojects?ref=RES-451-26-0456"><gtr:id>3C28513B-06CC-4EB6-A4AC-C5B9DE7DAC08</gtr:id><gtr:title>Conflicts in Time: Rethinking 'Contemporary' Globalisation</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Research Grant</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>RES-451-26-0456</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>The aim of this project was to create an interdisciplinary research network to examine the changing management and experience of time in the contemporary world. Globalisation has been widely analysed as an alteration in experiences of space, but we shifted the focus to time. In order to achieve this we used each workshop to examine institutions that mediate between different representations, experiences, rhythms and disciplines of time. These included museums, planning bureaucracies, global workplaces and social movements. Each workshop addressed one of these sites for the negotiation of time and brought together in a dialogue both academics and practitioners. Research findings from multiple regions of the world were always included in our conversations. In these discussions we uniquely addressed global changes to time that have occurred across the creative industries, bureaucracy, activism and labour.&lt;/p>

&lt;p>From these workshops we refuted assumptions about the emergence of a homogenous experience of global time through empirical findings. We also developed a new theoretical model through which to understand time. This analyses each social situation as a time-scape or a conflictual field of mediating acts and representations that seek to make time sensually present, manipulable and subject to various framing idioms.&lt;br />&lt;br />&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2011-03-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2008-03-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>14524</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutput><gtr:description>One of four ethnographic films addressing livelihoods, uncertainty and time on the Hooghly river. Shown at a public film showing at L.S.E. in May 2010 and at exhibition at Hastings Arts Forum March 2011. Also shown at Persistence/Resistence Indian Documentary Film Festival held across the University of London in November 2011. In addition I have used these films in regular teaching on a first year undergraduate course (AN102) on ethnographic methods and forms of representation since 2010.</gtr:description><gtr:id>183B0DA2-B04C-4E02-9A56-E03553CF3BE5</gtr:id><gtr:impact>Audience members at all three events, and undergraduates taught at LSE, have stated in discussions after film viewings and in written comments that it has altered their perspective.</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>r-7598374204.3360829c9ef85e</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:title>Ma ganga navigation</gtr:title><gtr:type>Film/Video/Animation</gtr:type><gtr:yearFirstProvided>2010</gtr:yearFirstProvided></gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutput><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutput><gtr:description>One of four ethnographic films add